{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505648"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:33:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:33:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2463"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2463"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.56,0.27,0.08,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115996"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2463"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97991"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"4891"},{"type":"tags","id":"6563"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2040"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2047"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49597"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115996"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 30-minute episode of blurring of vision affecting his right eye that occurred earlier in the day. His vision has now returned to normal. He has a medical history of myocardial infarction and coronary stent insertion two years ago. His regular medications are aspirin and atorvastatin. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min and regular, blood pressure 132/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. He has bilateral carotid bruits. Ophthalmological assessment reveals several cholesterol emboli in the right retina. A carotid duplex ultrasound study shows 60% stenosis in both proximal internal carotid arteries. A CT of the head is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue the current regimen and review","Start clopidogrel and right carotid endarterectomy","Bilateral carotid endarterectomy","Bilateral carotid angiography","Start apixaban"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a transient ischaemic attack (TIA) affecting the right eye, known as amaurosis fugax. This is considered symptomatic carotid artery stenosis, as the patient has experienced a TIA in a region supplied by the right carotid artery. The management of carotid artery stenosis depends on whether it is symptomatic or asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting clopidogrel and right carotid endarterectomy \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most appropriate next step. For symptomatic carotid stenosis \u0026gt;50%, urgent referral for carotid endarterectomy is recommended to significantly reduce the risk of future stroke. Adding clopidogrel to the current antiplatelet therapy (aspirin) is appropriate in this acute setting to reduce the risk of further events while awaiting definitive treatment. The referral for surgical intervention should be urgent, as the risk of stroke is highest in the weeks following a TIA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing the current regimen and review\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient for symptomatic carotid stenosis. This approach is more appropriate for asymptomatic carotid stenosis, where medical management and risk factor modification are the mainstays of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral carotid endarterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate. While the patient has bilateral carotid stenosis, only the right side is symptomatic. The left carotid artery stenosis is considered asymptomatic and does not require surgical intervention at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral carotid angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary in this case. The carotid duplex ultrasound has already provided sufficient information about the degree of stenosis. If further imaging is required, non-invasive options such as CT or MR angiography would be preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting apixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated. Apixaban is an anticoagulant used primarily for stroke prevention in atrial fibrillation. This patient has a regular pulse and no indication of atrial fibrillation. Moreover, anticoagulation is not the standard treatment for carotid stenosis and could increase the risk of bleeding complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, symptomatic carotid stenosis \u0026gt;50% requires urgent evaluation for carotid endarterectomy. The addition of clopidogrel and referral to a vascular surgeon or specialist TIA service is the most appropriate next step to reduce the risk of stroke in the critical period following the TIA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Symptomatic carotid stenosis \u003E50% should be managed with urgent referral for carotid endarterectomy.","Asymptomatic carotid stenosis should be managed medically with cardiovascular risk factor treatment. Carotid endarterectomy is indicated in only highly selected cases."],"references":["Biller J, Thies WH. When to operate in carotid artery disease. Am Fam Physician. 2000 Jan 15;61(2):400-6. PMID: 10670506. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10670506/","Managing asymptomatic carotid stenosis. In: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. [online]. 2019. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgAccess","Naylor AR, Ricco JB, de Borst GJ, Debus S, de Haro J, Halliday A Editor\u0027s Choice - Management of Atherosclerotic Carotid and Vertebral Artery Disease: 2017 Clinical Practice Guidelines of the European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS). Eur J Vasc Endovasc Surg. 2018 Jan;55(1):3-81. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28851594/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97991"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2463"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97991"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T08:51:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T08:52:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2463"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115996"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","syn